<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-435-131  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 435 131.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  Sept 17 1990 v9 n20 p38(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Wang awaits NSA go-ahead for encryption product. (WangLaboratories Inc. to manufacture its Trusted Interface Unit Type 1cryptography product after receiving permission from the USNational Security Agency)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Masud, S.A.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Wang Laboratories Inc. (product development).andO;Ticker:    WAN.andO;Product:   Wang Trusted Interface Unit-1 (Computer peripheral) (productdevelopment).andO;Topic:     Government AgencyEncryptionProduct DevelopmentData SecurityCommunications TappingCryptographyUnited States. National Security Agency.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Wang Awaits NSA Go-Ahead for Encryption ProductandM;Wang Laboratories Inc. is close to getting the go-ahead from the NationalSecurity Agency to manufacture a Type 1 cryptography product for securecommunications.andM;An NSA spokeswoman confirmed that Wang and the agency soon will sign amemorandum of understanding marking the completion of the developmentalevaluation phase for Wang's Trusted Interface Unit (TIU-1).andP;  The agreementalso begins the formal device evaluation process that could lead to NSAendorsement.andM;The TIU-1 is a standalone unit for encrypting and decrypting all levels ofgovernment classified information over 802.3 local area networks and variouswide area links, Wang officials said.andP;  It also supports the DefenseDepartment's Internet Protocol for data communications, they said.andM;Although each TIU-1 supports a single security level, it permits segregationof security communities at different levels, said David Berry, marketingmanager for the secure system program in Wang's Federal Systems Division.andO;Generally up to 18 users can share a single TIU-1, although Wang has testedthe product with more people, Barry said.andM;The TIU-1's keying material is distributed manually via smart keys, which aresmall electronics storage devices for loading configuration information intothe TIU-1.andP;  The keys are filled using a key management loader that consistsof an IBM compatible personal computer, interactive menu driven software anda single or four slot key adaptor box.andM;Wang is developing the device under the Commercial Comsec Endorsement Programestablished by a 1986 presidential directive.andP;  Communications securitymodules under this program contain an NSA-supplied encryption algorithm on asealed chip.andM;Wang officials said they expect NSA to endorse the device next February afterwhich it will be available for immediate delivery.andP;  Its price will start atabout $8,000.andM;Contact Powell Glenn, Wang's Comset program manager, tel.andP;  508-967-8699.andO;</TEXT></DOC>